    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-07-05T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-07-05T03:00:00-05:00" n="722"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d722">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">690D.91/7–S52; Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Pakistan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WAM1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Warren</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d722fn1">This telegram was repeated for information to
                        London and New York.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Karachi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-07-05T13:00:00+05:00"
                            >July 5, 1952—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>23. Immediately upon receipt of <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>’s nr. 31,
                    July 4, 4 p.m., I saw <gloss target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> and <gloss
                        target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss> separately this a.m. They said as
                    assumptions in para 1 are correct and understand that I am to tel <gloss
                        target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BCB1">Bowles</persName> immediately so that under the
                        <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>’s authorization he may see <persName
                        corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> on this matter. <persName
                        corresp="#p_KCSM1">Zafrulla</persName> said that if <persName
                        corresp="#p_BCB1">Bowles</persName> transmits the Pakistan offer without
                    first sounding out <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> on his
                    willingness to agree to the immediate appointment of the pleb administrator,
                    there is little likelihood of <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss>’s acceptance
                    of the proposal. The suggestion from both the <gloss target="#t_PriMin1"
                        >PriMin</gloss> and <persName corresp="#p_KCSM1">Zafrulla</persName> is that
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCB1">Bowles</persName> shld first ascertain if
                        <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> is willing to agree to the immed
                    formal designation of the pleb admin, provided an agreement can be reached on
                    the quantum of troops. If <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> is not
                    prepared to agree to the appointment, then the <gloss target="#t_Pak1"
                        >Pak</gloss>s are <pb facs="0221" n="1271" xml:id="pg_1271"/> unwilling for
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCB1">Bowles</persName> to present their four to one
                    offer on troop proportions in <gloss target="#t_IN1">Ind</gloss>-held Kashmir
                    and <persName corresp="#p_AMAK1">Azad</persName> Kashmir. On the other hand if
                        <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> expresses a willingness to agree
                    to the pleb admins formal appointment immed, provided an agreement can be
                    reached on troop quantum, he may then present the <gloss target="#t_Pak1"
                        >Pak</gloss> offer. The <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>s feel that if
                        <persName corresp="#p_NJ1">Nehru</persName> is not prepared to come down to
                    a maximum of 15,000 (excluding the 6,000 militia) then their offer of a four to
                    one proportion (excluding the 3,500 northern scouts) cannot be made.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_KCSM1">Zafrulla</persName> added that in case <persName
                        corresp="#p_BCB1">Bowles</persName>’ overtures are not successful, then the
                        <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss>s feel <persName corresp="#p_GDF1"
                        >Graham</persName> must be prepared to recommend to the <gloss
                        target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> (1) an immed formal appointment of the pleb
                    administrator and (2) a quantum of forces at this stage to be in proportion to
                    the cease-fire numbers as Devers may determine.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WAM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Warren</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
